rComments: He's very knowledgeable and sharp. He knows his material. The class is a bit too theoretical and too much math is needed as pre-req. But I learned a lot and suggest taking his courses. It's one of those classes that you actually learn stuff if you attend.

Dr. Etemad is very knowledgeable in his research areas and nanotechnology subjects.He is one on the best teachers I ever had. I past renewable energy graduate course with him and I learned a lot through this course.
I love him.He is a great professor.

Things I would rather do than attend his classes: Shave with a cheese grater, swallow my own tongue, put my hand in a meat grinder... hopefully you get my point: attending one of his classes is one of the most painfully boring experiences of life. On the plus side is seems like an alright guy and gave the easiest final exam I've ever had.

Boring is a compliment.In 10 minutes you want to gauge your eyes out with your hands.After class is done you feel like you have died.He says "VERY VERY IMPORTANT" on all 1000 slides.He teaches for 3 hours,if he has 5 minutes left,he WILL start a new chapter.Forget marks,by the time you get to the end of the course,you'll have no love for the world

Most boring prof I ever had. Assignments and exams are relatively easy, but there were 3 midterms and a group presentation; a bit heavy for just an elective course in my opinion. As a person he is nice, but he is a terrible prof. Tells you not to learn by heart, but that's what the course is all about, and man is there a lot to remember.Avoid him.
Terribly teacher. Vague, monotone, disorganized and loves to ask extremely obtuse pop-questions and put you on the spot in class.
